The younger Chabons kept telling me #Andor was really good, but even though I trust their taste and I wanted to believe them, I was skeptical, as I have been skeptical to one degree or another about every incoming #StarWars project since, I suppose, exiting the theater after the movie currently known as number 6 (? It will always be 3 to me) with the jubilation of Ewoks lingering irritatingly in my mind. And sadly that skepticism has only rarely proven unjustified. But, damn! Andor *is* really good! The production design is thrilling—the show revives the worn, dilapidated, stained, “Everything is Broken” texture of number 1 (my number 1) and takes it a step further, in a way that supports and deepens the story. The cast is top to bottom excellent. The writers have given thought to what words like empire and repression and liberation and freedom and sacrifice might really mean, and how those meanings can change in changed contexts. And most of all, in the skilled hands of #TonyGilroy Andor manages, while being huge and expensive and exciting and, well, Star Wars, to draw strength from virtues I associate with much smaller-scale shows I’ve shouted out recently, such as The Bear and Reservation Dogs: rooting the story in the characters, allowing those characters time to grow and develop, giving the actors time within scenes to find ways of saying things that can’t be conveyed as powerfully in words, trusting the audience’s intelligence. When you walk into a record store, the cassette section (yes, record stores have cassette sections again) won’t be just filled with old cassettes, but rather freshly shrink-wrapped albums from the past week. A format that was once considered a thing of the past and the reason album sales declined—due to the ease of pirating music—has been slowly making its way back along with the vinyl revival. Cassette sales are up, and 2023 is predicted to be an even bigger year for the format.

But why are cassettes back? Huge artists like Taylor Swift and The Weeknd have released cassette versions of their current and previous albums. Movies and TV shows like Guardians of the Galaxy, 13 Reasons Why, and Stranger Things have also had cassettes centered as a major prop. All these factors have helped introduce the format to a young, curious generation of music buyers. Those familiar with the format may consider cassettes to be low-fidelity but, as with vinyl, the quality of your listening experience depends on the equipment you use to play your music. Finding the right equipment is a little more difficult for cassettes, as the industry continues to catch up with the format's return. I can’t remember if I posted on here when I finished #WarrenZanes’s fantastic 2015 biography of #TomPetty, one of the three best music bios I read over quarantine, when I went on a bit of a music bio binge.* #delivermefromnowhere, due 5/2/23, is something else: the biography of an album, #brucespringsteen’s singular classic, #nebraska. Zanes’s book shares certain features with the strongest books in the (unrelated) 33 1/3 series— singular focus, thorough research, unabashed passion for and devotion to its subject, a strong yet not unwelcome authorial presence and, above all, a compelling argument to make—in this case that Springsteen’s weird, gothic, heartbroken 1982 left turn, equally the product of an acute psychological crisis and the introduction of the TEAC 144 PortaStudio, opened the door to and laid the groundwork for the whole lo-fi, 4-track, homebrew, backpack-and-laptop indie revolution that followed. But a few things make Zanes’s book, like his *Petty*, special: 1) his unique background as both a trained academic *and* a former member of a hard-working, tour-wracked, boom-then-bust roots rock ‘n’ roll band (80’s phenoms the #thedelfuegos), 2) direct access to the artist, 3) an unusual empathy underlying his insightful intellect and 4) a genuine, often astonishing writerly gift. Several times I found myself stopping to reread a sentence to admire its construction and the light it deftly shone on some particular of the book’s real subject, which is not just a startling swerve in the career of a great American artist, or a pivotal yet neglected transitional moment in the history of recorded music but the question Springsteen asked himself, forty years ago: what to do when you begin to understand that the things you have loved most have begun to do you harm?

*The other two: #robchapman’s #AVeryIrregularHead (Syd Barrett), and #RobinDGKelley’s #TheloniusMonk.

And now #TomVerlaine. Unlikely guitar hero in a scene and at a moment that scorned virtuosity, but to me—from the first startling, dislocating time I heard #MarqueeMoon circa 1981—always something more than that. His playing blew the dust off the way you thought about and heard a rock guitar; his approach to lyrics, poetic and colloquial, helped shape my own writing voice. I never met him but right now I feel like I’m grieving a mentor, a great teacher. An artist.

Listening again for the millionth time, and the music *still* holds surprises for the ear, and the lyrics *still* tremble invitingly just this side of unveiling their meaning, and maybe that’s one definition of “masterpiece.” Somebody, probably a Frenchman, said that every masterpiece either invents or exhausts a genre, but that the greatest do both those things at once. That fits #marqueemoon too. 

Punk is always characterized as having deliberately killed the cult of rock virtuosity, of spitting on the grave of long “noodling” solos, let alone musicians who, like Verlaine and #RichardLloyd, sat down to play. The music on this record could not by most definitions be considered punk, until you heard the singer’s brash sneer (albeit mingled with aching and wonder)—the nerve of that punk! I was about the same age when I first heard this record as Verlaine when he wrote “Venus,” and though I might not then (or now) have been able to say for certain what exactly he meant by “the world was so thin/between my bones and skin“, I was (and remain) absolutely certain that they described exactly how it felt to *be* that age, abroad in the big world, endlessly ready to fall into the elusive illusive arms of Venus de Milo. #riptomverlaine [Alt cover art by me, circa 2016]

A tentative playlist taxonomy, on dropping of my latest (link in profile). They (often with overlap):

A. Express, declare, or attempt to capture or describe the state of one’s feelings, recurrently or right now, about another person, a moment in time, or the world. 

B. Take a core sample of this particular moment in your listening life, for handy reference now (but, eventually, as an often powerful artifact/time capsule of a fleeting era in your life as a whole). 

B. Chart or document a history, craft a portrait, or make a thumbnail sketch or snapshot of an artist and their career (or a phase therein), of a musical scene or period, of a musical idea or innovation, of a genre or sub-genre, of a city or region, of a particular kind of song or song lyric, of an individual instrument or tempo or style of play or timbre of voice.

C. Catalog a particular lyrical theme or motif, e.g., breakup songs, dis tracks, songs about dogs or falling in love; songs about feeling big feelings (and expressing them with a histrionic or self-dramatizing flair). 

D. Create a certain vibe, real or imagined, through careful track selection, ideally discovering secret affinities among disparate artists and tracks.

E. Score an activity, including but not limited to exercising, road-tripping, fucking, partying, dancing (with others or alone), traveling to places with strong musical identities, engaging in artistic or other creative work, studying, cleaning the house, moping, pining, remembering, venting, falling asleep, inducing a child to fall asleep, etc; feeling, and expressing, big feelings. 

F. State a musical case or make a musical argument, e.g., Prince is an important power pop artist; there is a revealing kinship between the vocals of David Cassidy and the Gin Blossoms Robin Wilson. (This type is most vulnerable to failure, in my experience, generally for lack of evidence or triviality of thesis.)

G. Tell or unfold a story, real or imagined, through the careful sequencing of tracks. Pure instances of this type are rare in my listography (see Robert and Shirley), but sometimes as with Big Feelings, I’ll use a loose narrative structure or progression as a kind of armature.

While searching for something utterly unrelated, stumbled on these fantastic illustrations from the Helvetica Era of #BoysLife magazine—my era (Bobcat through 1st Class, then out). It’s for a late entry in the “Time Machine” series of short stories, by Donald Keith (an unusual father-son writing team, apparently), which featured the mostly comic adventures of a time-traveling scout patrol. Boys’ Life published a lot of fiction, bless them (Heinlein, Clarke, the “Mad Scientists Club”), and a few years after this issue it became the locus of my first editorial submission as a writer (and first rejection, see somewhere way back in this feed). But it only rarely featured fiction on its cover. This must have been too eye-popping to resist—but I’ve searched Google’s archived pages (whence these images) and was unable to identify the apparently uncredited illustrator. Anyone know?

Big thanks to @ogdencreative for identifying the illustrator from my previous post as #AlParker (1906-1985), unknown to me until today but to whom I’m now prepared to refer in future, after an hour spent googling his work (some of which is familiar to me though I had no idea whose it was) as the *great* Al Parker. I remember the summer of 2000 as unusually fine, and shadowed. High skies, riotous blooms of jasmine. But that April, after testing showed severe genetic abnormality, Ayelet and I had chosen to terminate a pregnancy at 18 weeks—ending an imagined third child we’d all begun, in our child or adult ways, to incorporate into the world of our then-family of four. 

We were reeling. Brightest sunshine, deepest shadow. 

That summer I decided to revive a custom I’d learned from my friend @alantacosta, of providing the imminent season with a mixtape that would become its soundtrack, typically a mix of new or recent releases/discoveries and favorites with a summery vibe. I had made tapes for Summers 1989-93, (see the locally legendary “Summer ‘92” playlist, one of the founding documents of Ayelet’s and my marriage), but had long since abandoned the practice. 

In 2000, however, we were entering the world of “ripping” and “burning” (What did we ever do to those guys/To make them so violent?), and my interest in the making of “mixtapes” suddenly revived. 

We played “Summer 2000” over and over that summer as we attempted to recover from our loss, to be present for our two beautiful living children, to get ready for the upcoming publication of a big dense novel I’d written—about comic books, of all things; and to somehow return, together, to feeling ready to try again, shaping another fragile vessel of our hopes and dreams. 

Recently, while combing through an old hard drive, I came upon a folder with a half-dozen .txt files exported from iTunes, including the track-listing for “Summer 2000.” The original burned CD-R—anyone remember #roxiotoast?—had long since vanished with those days.  But at some point after iTunes dropped, in 2001, I must have ripped it back in.

I reconstructed it today in Apple Music, and hit play. From the first broken-toy piano notes of “Happiest Guy,” I was awash in emotion and memory; then came Track 5 and I broke down. All that sunshine, all that darkness. But it’s a pretty great playlist, if I do say so myself. The song that best preserves like amber the feel of that summer is No Doubt’s incomparably sad “Simple Kind of Life.” Link in profile.

I never thought I could feel this way/And I've got to say that I just don't get it/I don't know where we went wrong/But the feeling's gone/And I just can't get it back

I at once understood what, or rather whom, he was singing about, even though I didn’t know how I knew, or how the words actually applied to them: he was singing about the two unhappy adults sitting up there in the front seat of our Dodge Coronet 440, giving each other the silent treatment mile after mile, heading ever deeper into the mystery and darkness of Gordon Lightfoot’s homeland, which was found on no map or atlas; that strange, shadowed, bittersweet kingdom one sometimes glimpsed in the densely-printed, convoluted pages of sober-faced paperback “adult” novels, the kind the drugstore sold. 

There is a short list of song lyricists who taught me the power of careful ellipsis in storytelling, the art of the telling blank, of depiction by indirection. Maybe that was where the Canadian in Lightfoot came most strongly into play. #ripgordonlightfoot

The big ♾️ loop clearly had to do with the solstices (summer at red arrow ) and equinoxes (blue arrow), but sometimes the big tarantula-blob of the sun shadow was way off the grid or even nowhere in sight, even on the sunniest days. For years now Agnes has worn a head halter (or head collar). It fits loosely with no pinching or constriction, and when we walk her on a leash with it, she never pulls, as she did even with a conventional harness, nor gags herself horrendously the way she did with a leash on a collar. 

Head halters are fairly common at home, but appear to be all but unknown here. Every time we go out in this dog-loving city, her halter arouses considerable interest and comment. People either think it’s *une muselière* (though if so it would be a really lame one) and ask anxiously (or doubtfully, given Agnes’s evident gentle nature), if she is *méchante*; or else they approach with a well-intentioned, slightly (or not so slightly) disapproving officiousness to inform me that, Monsieur! Attention! your dog’s leash has become entangled around her snout, and is blinding her, suffocating her, constricting her jaws!; these people, often women of my own age or older, were scandalized whenever I would smile, shake my head, and insist, with calm heartlessness or barbaric idiocy, *Non, ça va.*

I will confess, it got kind of annoying.

Then one day, faced with yet another, particularly alarmed *dame*, I had a sudden inspiration. I told her that it was only a leash. A special kind of leash. A 𝘊𝘢𝘭𝘪𝘧𝘰𝘳𝘯𝘪𝘢 leash.

*C’est une laisse californienne, madame*, I explained fraudulently. 

Instant relief. Reassurance. Even, it seemed to me: familiarity. Even: knowingness. What cultivated Parisian with an interest in dogs, after all, could fail to be aware of Californians and their kooky but enlightened innovations in gentle canine restraint?

*Ah, oui, une laisse californienne!*

She turned to the man at her side. 

*Tu vois, c’est une laisse californienne!* she informed him. 

*Mais bien sûr,* he intoned, with a knowledgeable nod. 

Works every time.

This started (and was mostly finished) as a COVID project. 

One endless quarantine afternoon, I was in my Berkeley studio, staring at my old #DAWSF and #BallantineAdultFantasy paperbacks, and contemplating, in my imagination, the “Science Fiction & Fantasy” section at the loooong-defunct Page One bookstore, back in #ColumbiaMD, where I grew up. 

People, I want to tell you, I fuckin HAUNTED that section! For YEARS! And now as I sat around communing with my tattered old friends, I discovered that I retained a sharp recollection—title, author, cover design—of what felt like every single book that had ever appeared on those tall shelves along the left wall of Page One, toward the back, between 1972 and 1980. 

So, writer by writer, title by title, designer by designer, I started to track down images, capturing them myself when I owned the book, downloading them from various websites when (most often) I did not. 

This collage—which I finally finished, last night—was the result. Think of it—I did—as a kind of time telescope, a look back at the visuals that embodied and accompanied my early aspirations as a writer, and at the mass-market splendor of paperback sf and fantasy in those days.

The great #AlexRoss’s recent piece in @newyorkermag about Franz Liszt, which turned me on to #yunchanlim’s astonishing 2022 Van Cliburn-winning performance of the “Transcendental Études,” started me on a quest to re-obtain this remarkable record, long out of print, which I first encountered shortly after it came out, in 1978. 

A great Liszt pianist needs, like Lim, like the man himself, to combine ultravirtuoso technique with volcanic expression. To that extent #ErvinNyerighyazi seems to have been the Lim of his day. Born in the pianistic wonderyear of 1903, prodigy (like Lim), absolute pitch, sight-reading phenom, debuted at 6, in the 1920s he *tore up* the concert halls with his “demonic” technique and flamboyant manner. Seems to have lived a total rock ’n’ roll lifestyle, washed up by 30, *nine* marriages, then disappeared completely, but *completely*, from the scene for forty years. Found his way to SF where in the late ’70s a friend coaxed him into doing a small recital, which another friend surreptitiously recorded. The recording circulated and eventually he was enticed to record this album of solo pieces—supporters and detractors alike call them “interpretations”—by his tutelary god. 

I remember a lot of music writers hated this record when it came out, hated N.’s “overblown” style, technical faults, lurching tempi, “wrong notes” (shades of Thelonious Monk’s critics), lack of sensitivity to nuance, etc. (An hour on the internet soon revealed that though the record is all but unavailable, the legion of haters has only grown—and they have YouTube channels. But the lovers are out there, too.) Heck, Alex Ross probably hates it!

Aged 15, 16, 17, I fucking loved it. I had never heard anything like it! Booming galloping roaring left hand, weeping dancing yearning right—everything going on at the keyboard was going on inside me. Storms and sorrows and revolutions! 

And now, at 60, calmer, wiser, well-acquainted with the limitations and liabilities of passion and unbridled feeling—I fucking love it. 

I eventually discovered a (ripped, presumably) version on YouTube, and made a playlist of it, if you can find your way to my YouTube channel, it’s there.

Here’s Cygnus, the Swan, flying high in the northern corner of the winter sky. The bright star at top in this photo is Deneb, one of the very brightest stars to our earthly eyes, possibly the most luminous of all in absolute terms (i.e. if it were not so vastly far away, ≈ 1500 light years!). Sometime around the year 9800 CE, thanks to precession of the equinoxes (a phenomenon that, like Great Britain’s monetary system before decimalization, I can truly grasp only so long as I am reading an explanation of it), it will have moved into position as Earth’s pole star, aligned with the northern axis of the planet’s rotation. My whole life I have swung between thrilling hope and utter desolation, sometimes over years, sometimes as now in the space of a minute, trying to imagine who or what might be around then to look up at Deneb, trusting in it to steer by.
Since I could not have imagined such a thing might even *be*, how could I have known it was exactly what I needed?

New playlist: Chilly Scenes of Winter. The other day, while I was driving down a road lined with bare trees, under gray skies, Al Stewart’s “Time Passages” happened to come on the radio. It perfectly fit the scene, and the autumnal tenor of my thoughts. Not because of its elegiac tone, or end-of-year setting, but because it was released in September 1978, and peaked at #7 on the US Top 100 in February 1979, and over that period, the fall and winter of my junior year of HS, I heard it 100s of times on the radio, more frequently the higher it climbed. After peaking, the song receded from my listening life to the extent that now when I hear it the experience is itself a time passage; sonically it encapsulates my subjective experience of that particular fall/winter—and then, by the powerful alchemy of memory and music, of all the falls and winters of my earliest music-fan life. Many other songs from back then have the same power, and here they are. For the most part they aren’t songs explicitly *about* fall or winter. It’s really a coincidence that, by the association of sonics (a lot
of strings, I note) with a massive but attenuated period of intense exposure in the chilly midst of darkening days, they magically summon up remembrance of autumns and winters past. Assembled here, they serve as a pleasurably bittersweet soundtrack for my own seasonally triggered bouts of melancholy. Thinking some of my fellow 70s kids will find it works for them, too. Our work at Breaking the Silence is based on testimonies given by IDF soldiers who served in the Occupied Territories. Collecting and verifying these testimonies is a long and complex process, and it will be quite some time before we get a full and accurate picture of what’s happening on the ground now.

We’ve spent years studying and publishing testimonies of soldiers who served in previous Israeli military campaigns in Gaza. One of those testimony booklets published was centered around the last time there was a ground incursion into the Gaza Strip in 2014 during Operation “Protective Edge”:

The booklet is a collection of testimonies from over 60 IDF soldiers that served in various units – from ground, naval, and air forces, to headquarters and command centers. About 25% of them were officers. Their testimonies exposed the nature of IDF operations in various combat zones.

While the testimonies include pointed descriptions of specific events and behavior by soldiers in the field, the more disturbing picture that arose from these testimonies reflected systematic policies that were dictated to IDF forces of all ranks and in all zones.

These principles and policies led to massive and, as of then, unprecedented harm to the civilian population and infrastructure in the Gaza Strip.

Part of understanding what is unfolding now needs to be based on what we already know happened in the past.

Some of my playlists are love offerings (I count 9 for @ayeletw to date) or in the nature of gifts or messages to my children, loved ones and friends. Some constitute a form of autobiography or memoir. Some are anthological or explanatory, attempting to characterize or define a musical genre or subgenre or sub-subgenre, or to represent a particular artist or period or label. Many are thematic, or conceptual. Others—the hardest and most engaging, for me, the ones I argue and debate with myself and revise endlessly—try to capture or create a particular vibe or mood, to mark a season or moment. And many, like this latest, are a combination of purposes and types. #SweetCherryWine started with its title song, a wonderful, lesser-known hit by #TommyJamesandtheShondells, which I’ve always loved for its gently trippy, bubblegum soulfulness—its vibe. In seeking to sustain the “sweet and heady” mood the song creates, however, I ended up confining myself to—and, I think, partly delineating—a period; working a seam and inhabiting a moment where psychedelic rock, sunshine & chamber pop, and blue-eyed soul often intertwined; and, in building out the list with other minor hits by major acts, or half-remembered misses by unknown wonders, creating a reminder of a bygone adventuresomeness and depth—and a sweetness—that flowed onto the radio and pop charts in the wake of #RubberSoul. Thundering drums, skirling guitars, synth lines soaring and swooping like endless aerial shots of moors and ancient forests, a singer calling out to the natural world in a plaintive clarion voice… Here’s “A Church Not Made With Hands,” a playlist celebrating the remarkable persistence of capital-R British and Celtic Romanticism—defined here as a longing for a return to and return of, wildness, for reunion of the natural world and the wildness within. 

The Romantic impulse had a celebrated musical flowering with the postwar British folk revival, and again in the work of Van Morrison, folk-rock pastoralists like the Incredible String Band, and in a strand of ultra-English prog rock exemplified by Jethro Tull and early Genesis.

But then the Lamb lay down on Broadway, and there was glam, punk, post-punk: past-rejecting, anti-nostalgic, or inverted-Romantic music that offered, dourly or gleefully, critiques, lamentations, and glorifications of artifice and the artificial world. Fundamentally urban music, sometimes ecstatic, more often dystopian. The music of a Ballardian world of concrete, plastic, and television. 

In 1977, while waiting for the Fairlight to be invented, and having left Genesis for good, Peter Gabriel recorded “Solsbury Hill,” which started out quietly invoking its folk-rock (Martin guitar, flute) and prog (7/4 time signature) Romantic musical heritage, before mounting, like the singer to the titular Bath hilltop, to something big and echoing and grand but also unabashedly pop, a kind of music that eight years later an NME writer, referring to the work of Mike Scott and the Waterboys, would characterize as “a Spectoresque whirlwind of sound, almost every lyric expressing an epic sentiment, every vocal almost a shout.” 

Thus in the late 70s Britain was Epic Romanticism* born. It was never a widespread or densely populated sub-genre, and it sputtered and faded, but at its peak it produced some genuinely sublime tracks, my favorites among them collected here. Follow link in profile. 

*Not to be confused with the synth-drenched post-*Low* dance-pop of the New Romantics.

Hitchcock and a fine pickup band of locals (including personal fave #kelleystoltz on drums, here glimpse-able behind Robyn) played an all-Barrett show to honor rock ’n’ roll’s brightest blown-out mind on what would have been the Floyd founder’s 84th birthday. Starting solo on quieter numbers drawn mainly from Barrett’s three wonderfully broken post-Floyd solo albums (highlight: the almost unbearably poignant and plaintive “Dark Globe“), Hitchcock brought on the band to play “Bike“, “Chapter 24” and other tracks from #Piper, “See Emily Play,” “Arnold Layne,” “Vegetable Man,” and a flawless selection of the heavier, trippier, up-tempo and/or more raucous numbers from the solo work, including “Gigolo Aunt,” “Octopus,” “Baby Lemonade,” and an awesome blues-forward cover of “Rats.” Hitchcock’s own fire was kindled in significant measure by his exposure to Syd Barrett’s work, and it was a joy to be present as the pupil, turned master himself, paid loving homage to that inspiration. Also great: the vintage-1967 UFO Club-style lighting effects.
